#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:1
msgid "New vtkImplicitArrays!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:3
msgid "Description"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:5
msgid ""
"VTK now offers new flexible `vtkImplicitArray` template class that "
"implements a **read-only** `vtkGenericDataArray` interface. It essentially "
"transforms an implicit function mapping integers to values into a "
"practically zero cost `vtkDataArray`. This is helpful in cases where one "
"needs to attach data to data sets and memory efficiency is paramount."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:7
msgid "Philosophy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:9
msgid ""
"In order to reduce the overhead of these containers as much as possible, "
"`vtkImplicitArray`s are templated on a \"Backend\" type. This backend is "
"\"duck typed\" so that it can be any const functor/closure object or "
"anything that has a `map(int) const` method to provide a certain degree of "
"flexibility and compute performance that is easily obtained through the "
"static dispatching native to templates. If a `void mapTuple(vtkIdType, "
"TupleType*) const` method is also present, the array will use this method to "
"populate the tuple instead of the map method. If a `ValueType "
"mapComponent(vtkIdType, int) const` method is also present, the array will "
"use this method to populate the GetTypedComponent function instead of the "
"map method. As such, developers can use tried and tested backends in the VTK "
"framework when it fits their needs and also develop their own backends on "
"the fly for specific use cases. `vtkImplicitArray`s can then be packed into "
"data sets to be transmitted through the data treatment pipeline with the "
"idea that calls to the \"read-only\" API of `vtkGenericDataArray` should be "
"inlined through the implicit array and generate close to zero overhead with "
"respect to calling the backend itself."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:11
msgid "Usage"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:13
msgid "Here is a small example using a constant functor in an implicit array:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:15
msgid ""
"struct ConstBackend\n"
"{\n"
"  int operator()(int vtkNotUsed(idx)) const { return 42; };\n"
"};\n"
"\n"
"vtkNew<vtkImplicitArray<ConstBackend>> arr42;\n"
"arr42->SetNumberOfComponents(1);\n"
"arr42->SetNumberOfTuples(100);\n"
"CHECK(arr42->GetValue(77) == 42); // always true\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:27
msgid ""
"Here is a small example using map and mapTuple methods in an implicit array:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:29
msgid ""
"struct ConstTupleStruct\n"
"{\n"
"  int Tuple[3] = { 0, 0, 0 };\n"
"\n"
"  ConstTupleStruct(int tuple[3])\n"
"  {\n"
"    this->Tuple[0] = tuple[0];\n"
"    this->Tuple[1] = tuple[1];\n"
"    this->Tuple[2] = tuple[2];\n"
"  }\n"
"\n"
"  // used for GetValue\n"
"  int map(int idx) const\n"
"  {\n"
"    int tuple[3];\n"
"    this->mapTuple(idx / 3, tuple);\n"
"    return tuple[idx % 3];\n"
"  }\n"
"  // used for GetTypedTuple\n"
"  void mapTuple(int vtkNotUsed(idx), int* tuple) const\n"
"  {\n"
"    tuple[0] = this->Tuple[0];\n"
"    tuple[1] = this->Tuple[1];\n"
"    tuple[2] = this->Tuple[2];\n"
"  }\n"
"};\n"
"\n"
"vtkNew<vtkImplicitArray<ConstTupleStruct>> mapTupleArr;\n"
"int tuple[3] = { 1, 2, 3 };\n"
"mapTupleArr->ConstructBackend(tuple);\n"
"mapTupleArr->SetNumberOfComponents(3);\n"
"mapTupleArr->SetNumberOfTuples(100);\n"
"int tuple[3] = { 0, 0, 0 };\n"
"mapTupleArr->GetTypedTuple(77, tuple);\n"
"CHECK(tuple[0] == 1 && tuple[1] == 2 && tuple[2] == 3); // always true\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:67
msgid ""
"Here is a small example using map and mapComponent methods in an implicit "
"array:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:69
msgid ""
"struct ConstComponentStruct\n"
"{\n"
"  int Tuple[3] = { 0, 0, 0 };\n"
"\n"
"  ConstComponentStruct(int tuple[3])\n"
"  {\n"
"    this->Tuple[0] = tuple[0];\n"
"    this->Tuple[1] = tuple[1];\n"
"    this->Tuple[2] = tuple[2];\n"
"  }\n"
"\n"
"  // used for GetValue\n"
"  int map(int idx) const { return this->mapComponent(idx / 3, idx % 3); }\n"
"  // used for GetTypedComponent\n"
"  int mapComponent(int vtkNotUsed(idx), int comp) const { return this-"
">Tuple[comp]; }\n"
"};\n"
"\n"
"vtkNew<vtkImplicitArray<::ConstComponentStruct>> genericComponentConstArr;\n"
"int tuple[3] = { 1, 2, 3 };\n"
"genericComponentConstArr->ConstructBackend(tuple);\n"
"genericComponentConstArr->SetNumberOfComponents(3);\n"
"genericComponentConstArr->SetNumberOfTuples(50);\n"
"CHECK(genericComponentConstArr->GetTypeComponent(0, 0) == 1 && "
"genericComponentConstArr->GetTypeComponent(0, 1) == 2 && "
"genericComponentConstArr->GetTypeComponent(0, 2) == 3); // always true\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:95
msgid ""
"For convenience, a number of backends have been pre-packed into the "
"`vtkImplicitArray` framework. They are, in alphabetical order:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:97
msgid ""
"`vtkAffineArray<ValueType>`: using the `vtkAffineImplicitBackend<ValueType>` "
"closure backend that gets constructed with a slope and intercept and then "
"returns values linearly depending on the queried index"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:98
msgid ""
"`vtkCompositeArray<ValueType>`: using the "
"`vtkCompositeImplicitBackend<ValueType>` closure backend that takes an `std::"
"vector<vtkDataArray*>` at construction and returns values as if the list has "
"been concatenated into one array"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:99
msgid ""
"`vtkConstantArray<ValueType>`: using the "
"`vtkConstantImplicitBackend<ValueType>` closure backend that gets "
"constructed with a given value and then returns that same value regardless "
"of the index queried"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:100
msgid ""
"`vtkStdFunctionArray<ValueType>`: using a `std::function<ValueType(int)>` "
"backend capable of covering almost any function one might want to use"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:101
msgid ""
"`vtkIndexedArray<ValueType>`: using the "
"`vtkIndexedImplicitBackend<ValueType>` closure backend that takes an "
"indexing array (either `vtkIdList` or `vtkDataArray`) and a base "
"`vtkDataArray` at construction and returns values indirected using the "
"indexing array to give access to a shuffled array without the memory cost"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:103
msgid ""
"Here is a small code snippet example to illustrate the usage of the "
"`vtkConstantArray`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:105
msgid ""
"vtkNew<vtkConstantArray<int>> arr42;\n"
"arr42->ConstructBackend(42);\n"
"arr42->SetNumberOfComponents(1);\n"
"arr42->SetNumberOfTuples(100);\n"
"CHECK(arr42->GetValue(77) == 42); // always true\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:113
msgid ""
"Multi-component arrays have de-facto AOS ordering with respect to the "
"backend."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:115
msgid ""
"The read-only parts of the `vtkDataArray` API work out of the box for any "
"`vtkImplicitArray` including the following functionalities:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:116
msgid ""
"Get components, typed components, tuples, number of components and number of "
"tuples"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:117
msgid ""
"`vtkImplicitArray::GetVoidPointer` (implementing and internal deep copy of "
"the array into an AOS array that can be destroyed with `vtkImplicitArray::"
"Squeeze`)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:118
msgid ""
"Standard library like ranges and iterators using `vtkDataArrayRange` "
"functionalities"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:119
msgid ""
"`vtkArrayDispatch`, provided the correct compilation options have been set "
"and the correct type list is used for dispatching (see below)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:121
msgid "`NewInstance` behavior"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:123
msgid ""
"The `NewInstance` method is often used on arrays in cases where one has a "
"`vtkDataArray` and one wants a freshly constructed instance of the same type "
"without actually having to  determine its type by hand. The workflow often "
"goes on to populate the newly minted instance with transformed values from "
"the original array."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:125
msgid ""
"vtkSmartPointer<vtkDataArray> originalArr = SomeMethodProvidingAnArray();\n"
"vtkSmartPointer<vtkDataArray> newArr = vtk::TakeSmartPointer(originalArr-"
">NewInstance());\n"
"newArr->SetNumberOfTuples(1);\n"
"newArr->SetComponent(0, 0, originalArr->GetComponent(0, 0));\n"
"CHECK(originalArr->getComponent(0, 0) == newArr->GetComponent(0, 0));\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:133
msgid ""
"In the case of `vtkImplicitArray`s, this kind of approach will not work "
"since a `vtkImplicitArray` is by definition read-only."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:135
msgid ""
"In order for `vtkImplicitArray`s to behave nicely in areas where this kind "
"of workflow is implemented, the behavior of `vtkImplicitArray::NewInstance` "
"has been modified to return a new instance of "
"`vtkAOSDataArrayTemplate<vtkImplicitArray<BackendT>::ValueTypeT>` so that "
"explicit population of the new array with values from the previous array "
"will happen seamlessly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:137
msgid ""
"Of course, in this context, a call to `NewInstance` will not provide the "
"propagation of the implicit nature of the arrays and the new arrays will be "
"explicitly stored in memory."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:139
msgid "Focus on `vtkCompositeArrays`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:141
msgid ""
"The `vtkCompositeArray` is a family of `vtkImplicitArray`s that can "
"concatenate arrays together to interface a group of arrays as if they were a "
"single array. This concatenation operates in the \"tuple\" direction and not "
"in the \"component\" direction."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:143
msgid ""
"This new array relies on the `vtkCompositeImplicitBackend` template class to "
"join an `std::vector` of `vtkDataArray`s. The `vtkCompositeArray`s use "
"internal address referencing and indirection to implement binary search on "
"the indexes of the composite array leading to access with $O(log_2(m))$ time "
"where $m$ is the number of leaves (or base `vtkDataArray`s) composing the "
"composite."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:145
msgid ""
"To facilitate the creation of `vtkCompositeArray`s in practice, a templated "
"utility function `vtkCompositeArrayUtilities::Concatenate` has been made "
"available to users that can take an `std::vector` of `vtkDataArray`s (each "
"with the same number of components) and turn them into a single concatenated "
"`vtkCompositeArray` with the same number of components as the base array and "
"a number of tuples being the sum of all the base arrays tuples."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:147
msgid "A code snippet using this type of array:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:148
msgid ""
"std::vector<vtkDataArray*> baseArrays(16);\n"
"vtkNew<vtkDoubleArray> baseArray;\n"
"baseArray->SetNumberOfComponents(3);\n"
"baseArray->SetNumberOfTuples(10);\n"
"baseArray->Fill(0.0);\n"
"\n"
"std::fill(baseArrays.begin(), baseArrays.end(), baseArray);\n"
"vtkSmartPointer<vtkCompositeArray<double>> composite = "
"vtkCompositeArrayUtilities::Concatenate<double>(baseArrays); // nTuples = "
"160\n"
"\n"
"CHECK(composite->GetComponent(42, 1) == 0.0); // always true\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:161
#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:195
msgid "**WARNINGS**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:163
msgid ""
"Any two arrays composited into a `vtkCompositeArray` using the `vtk::"
"ConcatenateDataArrays` method must have the same number of components."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:164
msgid ""
"Iteration over the composited array incurs a lot of overhead compared to an "
"explicit memory array (~3x slower with only 1 level). The use case is truly "
"when memory efficiency is more important than compute performance"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:165
msgid ""
"This array has no relationship with the `VTKCompositeDataArray` present in "
"the `numpy_interface.dataset_adapter` module of the python wrapping of VTK"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:167
msgid "Focus on `vtkIndexedArray`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:169
msgid ""
"The family of `vtkIndexedArray`s allow you to wrap an existing "
"`vtkDataArray` with a layer of indirection through a list of indexes "
"(`vtkIdList` or another `vtkDataArray`) to create a derived subset data "
"array without any excess memory consumption. As such, by providing a "
"`vtkIndexedImplicitBackend` with an indexation array and a `vtkDataArray`, "
"one can effectively construct a reduced and reordered view of the base array."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:171
msgid ""
"While using this type of feature to create only one indexed array can be "
"counter productive (allocation of the index array more expensive than an "
"explicit copy of the data might be), using this feature you can share the "
"same index list amongst multiple indexed arrays effectively using less "
"memory total."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:173
msgid "Here is an example use case:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:174
msgid ""
"vtkNew<vtkIntArray> baseArr;\n"
"baseArr->SetNumberOfComponents(3);\n"
"baseArr->SetNumberOfComponents(100);\n"
"auto range = vtk::DataArrayValueRange<3>(baseArr);\n"
"std::iota(range.begin(), range.end(), 0);\n"
"\n"
"vtkNew<vtkIdList> indexes;\n"
"indexes->SetNumberOfIds(30);\n"
"for (idx = 0; idx < 30; idx++)\n"
"{\n"
"    indexes->SetId(ids, 10*idx);\n"
"}\n"
"\n"
"vtkNew<vtkIndexedArray<int>> indexed;\n"
"indexed->SetBackend(std::"
"make_shared<vtkIndexedImplicitBackend<int>>(indexes, baseArr));\n"
"indexed->SetNumberOfComponents(1);\n"
"indexed->SetNumberOfComponents(indexes->GetNumberOfIds());\n"
"CHECK(indexed->GetValue(13) == 130); // always true\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:197
msgid ""
"Significant access performance hits can be incurred due to cache missing "
"cause by the inherent indirection in the array."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:199
msgid "Implementing a `vtkImplicitArray` in VTK"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:201
msgid ""
"Implementing a new `vtkImplicitArray` in the VTK library usually passes "
"through the following steps:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:202
msgid ""
"Implementing the backend: this is the step where the underlying "
"functionality of the implicit array needs to be developed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:203
msgid ""
"Creating an alias and instantiating the concrete types: once the backend is "
"ready, one can create an alias for the array in its own header (`using "
"MySuperArray = vtkImplicitArray<MySuperBackend>`) and use this header and "
"the au    tomatic instantiation mechanisms present in `Common/ImplicitArrays/"
"CMakeLists.txt` to make sure that the vtk library gets shipped with pre-"
"compiled objects for your arrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:204
msgid ""
"Hooking up the dispatch mechanism: this step ensures that your new arrays "
"can be included in the `vtkArrayDispatch` mechanism when the correct "
"compilation option is set."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:205
msgid ""
"Testing: be sure to set up some tests in order to both verify that your "
"implementation is functioning correctly and to avoid regressions in the "
"future."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:207
msgid ""
"An example merge request that was used for including the `vtkIndexedArray`s "
"can be found here: [!9703](https://gitlab.kitware.com/vtk/vtk/-/"
"merge_requests/9703)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:209
msgid "Building and Dispatch"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:211
msgid ""
"The entire implicit array framework is included in the `CommonCore` module. "
"Support for dispatching implicit arrays can be enforced by including type "
"lists from `vtkArrayDispatchImplicitTypeList.h` and compiling VTK with the "
"correct `VTK_DISPATCH_*_ARRAYS` option."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:213
msgid ""
"vtkToImplicitArrayFilter: compress explicit memory arrays into a "
"`vtkImplicitArray`s"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:215
msgid ""
"You now have access to a new filter `vtkToImplicitArrayFilter` in a new "
"`FiltersReduction` module that can transform explicit memory arrays into "
"`vtkImplicitArray`s. The filter itself delegates the \"compression\" method "
"to a `vtkToImplicitStrategy` object using a strategy pattern."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:217
msgid ""
"The following strategies (in order of complexity) have been implemented so "
"far:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:218
msgid ""
"`vtkToConstantArrayStrategy`: transform an explicit array that has the same "
"value everywhere into a `vtkConstantArray`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:219
msgid ""
"`vtkToAffineArrayStrategy`: transform an explicit array that follows an "
"affine dependence on its indexes into a `vtkAffineArray`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:220
msgid ""
"`vtkToImplicitTypeErasureStrategy`: transform an explicit integral array "
"(with more range in its value type than necessary for describing it) into a "
"reduced memory explicit integral array wrapped in an implicit array."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:221
msgid ""
"`vtkToImplicitRamerDouglasPeuckerStrategy`: transform an explicit memory "
"array into a `vtkCompositeArray` with constant (`vtkConstantArray`) and "
"affine (`vtkAffineArray`) parts following a Ramer-Douglas-Peucker algorithm."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:223
msgid "`GetActualMemorySize` function for `vtkImplicitArray`s"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release_details/9.4/add-vtkImplicitArrays.md:225
msgid ""
"`vtkImplicitArray` backends can also define the method `getMemorySize` "
"returning an `unsigned long` value corresponding to their memory usage in "
"KiB. This value can then be accessed through `vtkImplicitArray`'s method "
"`GetActualMemorySize`. If the backend does not define `getMemorySize`, the "
"value returned by `GetActualMemorySize` will be 1."
msgstr ""
